description: Scholar, researcher and activist, Dr. Jahi Issa will speak on the "traditional" end of African American education at predominately white universities and colleges and historically black colleges and universities. Dr. Issa states that this new era represents a watershed moment in African American Educational pursuits since Brown vs. the Board of Education. His presentation will highlight research that details a possible more than 20 percent reduction in African Americans in higher education over the next 10 years. Dr. Issa will also detail the impact of the forthcoming Affirmative Action Supreme Court ruling, should it lead to it's dismantling. Dr. Issa says that all of the aforementioned could result in a devastating impact on progressive approaches to diversity education. This promises to be an engaging, important and informative lecture.
title: Lecture: The Possible Reduction of African Americans in Higher Education and End of Affirmative Action

description: Ellen D. Williams, a renowned physicist and chemist currently serving as the chief scientist for the British oil company BP, will speak at the University of Maryland on Thursday, April 18, 2013. As BP's chief scientist, Williams shows the company how developments in science and technology can contribute to sustainable, secure and environmentally responsible energy. She remains a professor at UMD, where her research group maps out the positions of individual atoms in very small structures to explore the consequences of fluctuations at the nanoscale. A joint presentation of the Maryland NanoCenter and the University of Maryland Energy Research Center.
title: NANOCOLLOQUIUM: Ellen Williams: A scientist's-eye view of research for sustainable energy

description: The graduate students of COMM698F Seminar in Feminist, Gender, and Queer Theories in Communication is sponsoring A DONATION DRIVE FOR CALVARY WOMEN'S SHELTER from APRIL 8-19, 2013, and we would greatly appreciate your donations of blankets, towels, washcloths, laundry soap pods, dish soap, deodorant, and ground coffee in *brand new* condition. Donation boxes will be placed in the main offices of the following on-campus departments: Communication (2130 Skinner), Women's Studies (2101 Woods), and American Studies (1101 Holzapfel). From humble beginnings as a single basement emergency shelter in 1983, Calvary Women's Shelter has worked tirelessly to provide housing, nutritional meals, educational and employment opportunities, mental health services, and addiction recovery support to women in need. You can learn more about Calvary, and other ways to get involved, at http://www.calvaryservices.org.
title: Calvary Women's Shelter Donation Drive

description: The Department of Plant Science and Landscape Architecture (PSLA) Lecture Series Presents Dr. Frank Martin, Research Plant Pathologist, USDA-ARS, Salinas, CA Seminar Title: " Mitochondrial genomics of Phytophthora and the search for molecular tools for pathogen 27 identification and detection" Research Interests: Ecology, biology, biological control, and genetics of fungal soilborne pathogens and other rhizosphere microflora. The current research responsibility with the USDA-ARS is the development of alternatives to methyl bromide for the strawberry and vegetable industry and the development of molecular markers for detection of pathogens controlled by methyl bromide. Specific interest is conducting research with phylogeny and detection of Pythium and Phytophthora and conducting research on detection and population biology of Verticillium dahliae. For more information or to meet with the speaker, please contact: Dr. Yilmaz Balci, ybalci@umd.edu
title: PSLA Lecture Series: 4//17 Dr. Frank Martin, 4:00 pm, PLS 1130, " Mitochondrial genomics of Phytophthora and the search for molecular tools for pathogen 27 identification and detection"

description: Funeral Parade of Roses Toshio Matsumoto | 1969 | 105 min. | Japanese with English Subtitles Funeral Parade of Roses is a loose adaptation of Oedipus Rex set in the underground gay counterculture of 1960s Tokyo. Notable for its cinéma vérité interventions that blur the lines between actors and their characters and its "pop" predispositions, the film was later a major aesthetic influence on Stanley Kubrick's 1971 film A Clockwork Orange. This event is free and open to the public. The screening will be followed by free pizza and a brief discussion.
title: International Film Series - Free Screening - Funeral Parade of Roses

description: On April 22, Baltimore rapper "King Los" will bring his talents to The University of Maryland as part of his "Becoming King" tour. After being signed by Diddy this past year, "King Los" is on the fast track to stardom, and his new mixtape, "Becoming King", will have features from Diddy, Wiz Khalifa, Pusha T, Juicy J, and many other notable rappers. Be sure to come out and enjoy the show, which begins at 7 PM in the Baltimore Room of the Stamp Student Union.
title: SEE Presents: BMore's Own: King Los

description: The next Google and University of Maryland Cybersecurity Seminar featuring Dr. Nicolas Christin, Associate Director of the Information Networking Institute at Carnegie Mellon University. The talk will occur on Wednesday, April 17, 2013 at 5:00 p.m. in the Computer Science Instructional Center, Lecture Hall 1115. The event is free and open to the campus community and friends in industry, government and non-profit organizations. Registration is required. Guests can register online for the talk by Dr. Nicolas Christin, titled "Network Security Economics: Identifying Choke Points and Understanding Incentives to Improve Online Security." at: https://talks.cs.umd.edu/talks/326 A brief reception will follow the talk. We hope to see you at this upcoming event.
title: Google and UMD Cybersecurity Seminar with Dr. Nicolas Christin

description: It's market day! Schedule a break, grab a co-worker or friend and join us in welcoming The Farmers Market at Maryland back to campus. Be one of the first 500 visitors and receive a free re-usable shopping tote. Check in on Foursquare for a special deal! Make it your lunch break and buy a delicious meal from Dining Services -- spring salad with maple crusted chicken breast, garlic roasted asparagus and a strawberry balsamic vinaigrette. Shopping at the market is a great way to celebrate Earth Week. Our market provides an opportunity to purchase food directly from local farms. The food doesn't travel long distances, so buying locally reduces the environmental impact of bringing food to your table. See you at the market!
title: The Farmers Market at Maryland Season Opening - TODAY

description: On April 18th and 19th from 12:30PM -- 4:30PM, the LGBT Staff and Faculty Association will be sponsoring a Service Day, cleaning up and planting new flowers and shrubs around Marie Mount Hall. This is open to the entire UMD community: undergraduates, graduate students, faculty, and staff. We are seeking volunteers, and are also asking that you share news of this with your colleagues and students. Find the sign-up below! The minimum commitment is 1-hour but you are more than welcome to sign up for more. Gloves and gardening tools will be provided, and staff from the Arboretum and Horticultural Services will supervise. Make sure to wear appropriate clothing that day for this activity. Please let me know if you have any questions!
title: LGBTSFA Service Day at Marie Mount Hall

description: American composer and singer-songwriter Gabriel Kahane, Orpheus Chamber Orchestra's first composer-in-residence, combines his classical music training with modern folk-pop influences. Kahane will perform with Orpheus in a program that includes his very recent composition titled Gabriel's Guide to the 48 States plus Arnold Schoenberg's Transfigured Night.
title: Orpheus Chamber Orchestra and Gabriel Kahane, 4/20 @ 8pm

description: Rebels on Campus - Why Being a Liberal on the College Campus is Really Boring UMD Republicans is proud to host New York Times bestselling author and journalist Katie Pavlich through the Clare Boothe Luce Policy Institute. She will be lecturing on political activism on the college campus - and why being a young liberal today isn't so unique. The lecture will take place on April 30th at 7PM in the Grand Ballroom Lounge of Stamp. This event is free and open to the public - and will include a short Q&A session following the lecture. Pavlich is the news editor for Townhall.com and contributing editor to Townhall Magazine. Her commentary has been featured on Fox News, CNN, MSNBC, and CNBC.
title: UMD College Republicans: Katie Pavlich Lecture

description: The Art and Learning Center and The Bureau, Maryland's only all-purpose comedy group, will be hosting a free improv workshop Thursday April 18th at 7 PM in the Art and Learning Center. The workshop will teach students "out of the box" thinking using humor and improv techniques. Students will learn unique techniques that are transferable to help them improve their public speaking, diffuse difficult situations, and make them think on their feet. Light refreshments will be provided, but space is limited to 20 participants. Registration is now open! http://thestamp.umd.edu/entertainment/art_learning_center/class_registration
title: Space running out: Free Improv Workshop at The Art & Learning Center
